Welcome to Fantasyland, I guess. Unreal. Good solid storyline. The entire time I watched this movie all I could think about are all the villagers in Northern China whose villages have been burned down to make way for expensive highrise ghost town communities that enslave elderly farm families who are forced to go into debt $80,000 and up just to live in these giant cold freezing cement kingdoms. And no more family farm for them :( A very sad outcome.
So for the poor people of China --- China is still a Communist Country?
Yet, for the filthy rich, China is a basic free for all. Hmm. I guess I don't understand any of it. And the Uighers, the Muslims, the Tibetans!(who I adore)--all enslaved, beaten down and supposed to be forgotten about.
This movie is what I call a Brain washing Commercial.
Can I say that? I am an American. God help us all if this is the future.
The Wedding scene was nice.
No offense to any Chinese people. I just think it was like "over the top"--maybe it's just me. The customs being passed down were nice. The movie has good intentions and if you don't know what's really going on in China, then it's fine.

Comment:
I love the representation in this movie.

Before I am bombarded with "Asians don't need representation" or "#doublestandards" or "not all asians are represented" etc. I want to clarify that I love the representation of Asians that live and grew up in the Western culture. I think this movie really touches home, except with my parents, they don't understand that asian kids in asia aren't the same as the kid from the same race in the west. I think we aren't focussing enough on the right representation. Sure the title can be a little misleading, and that there are some stereotypes present, but I think the main character was very well done.

The movie itself is subpar. The plot is unoriginal and there was no ‚Äòfeeling‚Äô or ‚Äòexcitement‚Äô- pretty boring and cheesy at times making some scenes super difficult to watch. 
No one can deny the overhype the cast has created simply because of an all Asian cast and its significance of ‚Äúdiversity.‚Äù From my understanding of the word diversity in this context, it is the portrayal of various different races, which the film simply does not do (where‚Äôs the diversity if it‚Äôs all Asians?) 
Lead actress Constance is such a cringe in and out of film. Her exaggerated pro-Asian stance is conflicted in her interviews where she displays a lack of knowledge in Asian culture and not to mention her inability to even speak her mother tongue. It seems more like an opportunity for her to rant about finally landing a job as a lead in a Hollywood film. (By the way, almost all the lead female actresses from the film are in real life dating white men and non Asian ethnicities. Hypocrisy?)
The support it seems does not accurately reflect the movie itself (which is what is should be based on) but the cast and making of. I see a lot of comments saying that it has made them ‚Äúproud‚Äù to be Asian, or that they ‚Äúcried because they‚Äôve never seen themselves in a positive way.‚Äù I‚Äôm sorry, but if you need to seek approval from Hollywood to accept yourself, then there‚Äôs more of an issue with you personally that I don‚Äôt think a movie can fix. Title: CRAZY RICH ASIANS - Official Trailer
Comment:
Lot's of fun spots that the audience all laughed , me included.
Yes it can be considered a chick flick, but if certain parts are done right ,like the music is in the wedding scene ,
then it becomes all inclusive. BTW, the wedding scene was right up their with Mamma Mia's HWGA Dancing Queen scene.
Very impressed with Jon M.Chu work here . 
Just a little FYI , if you're at an Asian function and the reply to your question " What does it taste like " ? is taste like hot dog ,
don't bite at the chance just to be cool and fit in, cause it doesn't . 
Also, when you ask what's the special soup of the day, and the cook tells you to open the pot , don't !
Especially if you don't want to look at a bunch of chicken feet.
I used to work at a restaurant called Frankies Chinese Steak House, and they got their fair share of giggles after I opened those pots and pans .
Top notch food though everyone . Seriously . Lobster sauce was from lobster. Peking Duck crispy damn delicious.
Real, not frozen stuff. Today most all restaurants won't deal with raw shimp etc, unless you live by the coasts,
and them some places still won't . 
Teriyaki on a stick , daaamnnnnnnnn . Jes holy moses good.
I used to help them make it.
Peppers & Steak , wow . Everything every morning done fresh.
I was 18/19 years old and doing a job as a bar back/bus boy and I was walking out the door on Fridays with $200 to $300,
a night.
The reason being , it was Frankies.
They worked hard, that's the reason for their success. Just bust ass hard workers.
That's the real reason for all their great grades too, they bust ass.
You don't go back home with bad grades.

I knew this one Asian girl in college. She was from China. 
She had straight A's. She had to make sure everything was completed even before she would ever consider going out.
It kinda drove me nuts at times , but she pleaded with me to respect her wishes, and not ask till everything was done.
I did. 
She moved back to China. I still have some of the letters we shared from all those years ago.
Wow, Crazy Rich Asian kinda affected me more than I thought it did.

Regarding the rich.
*New found tend to be apologetic* . 
I was supposed to go to NYC for the 4th, but my friend took us elsewhere .
We ended up at the top side of a mountain that overlooked the city from afar.
What was on the top was a house  that was built at the edge of the cliff of that mountain.
Literally , it was built into the rock top/side. 
If you went to the edge of the outside deck, the outside deck was the plot of most average house,
that comments just for scale, you could look straight down the cliff.
Well those people who owned that were the apologizing kind .
*Old money, well the gardener drinks from the garden hose* .

Regardless of my old ass ramblings , 
you'll laugh and love with Crazy Rich Asians .
Certainly worth a repeat viewing, especially the wedding scene .

Comment:
I total feel this movie. Normally Asian (read: East Asian) families are pretty elitist. In China, girls have a saying that they rather cry in a Benz than laugh on a bicycle. Yeah, it's a shitty mentality but that's what it is.

The key to shrug off parental influence is to be your own person. I know a lot of Asian kids who had to listen to every word their parents spew off mostly because they. are. not. independent. When your parents pays for your house and your car, you are damn sure to listen to them.

So if you want to find true love (not some random girl your parents like), first you have to find your own success; aka make your own money, carve out your own piece of the world with your own hands. That way, you don't need to listen to anyone or kaotow to anyone not even your loving parents.

As much as I love my parents, I have dated girls from every background and they have very little say in what happens. After a while, they just started to accept it. That is how you get your own life back. Nowadays, they are supportive and amazing.

Title: CRAZY RICH ASIANS - Official Trailer
Comment:
Great article analyzing the mahjong scene from Vox website (Spoiler alert if you have not seen the movie, and you should). Vulture site also has another good write up explaining the fine points many would miss.
 
"What the climactic mahjong scene means
In the movie, the mahjong scene takes place in a pivotal scene after our protagonist Rachel Chu, played by Constance Wu, has been rejected by her boyfriend Nick‚Äôs mother, Eleanor (played by Michelle Yeoh). This is because Eleanor learns that Rachel was born to a single mother who fled China for the States. However, unbeknownst to Eleanor, Nick has gone against his mother‚Äôs wishes and proposed to Rachel anyway.

In the mahjong scene, Rachel and Eleanor go head to head right after this stunning twist. Rachel invites Eleanor to meet with her at a mahjong parlor ‚Äî a gambling house frequented mostly by working- or middle-class older folks who rent tables by the hour. The persistent clacking of tiles is a sound familiar to anyone who has been around people playing mahjong.

When Eleanor arrives, she takes the open seat across from Rachel and is offered the role of dealer ‚Äî the ‚ÄúEast‚Äù seat. The four seats in mahjong are named after the compass directions, which plays an important role both in the rules of the game and in the symbolism of the scene. Eleanor, in the role of the ‚ÄúEast,‚Äù representing Asia, is the player in control. Rachel, sitting across from her, represents America ‚Äî the ‚ÄúWest.‚Äù

Early in the scene, Eleanor completes a ‚Äúpong,‚Äù or a matched set of tiles. This move demonstrates that Eleanor plans to win using the strategy of matched tiles, and she‚Äôs making Rachel aware. In this moment, Eleanor tells Rachel that her mother taught her how to play too.

As the conversation continues, Rachel asks Eleanor why she didn‚Äôt like her from the very beginning ‚Äî even before her family history was revealed. Eleanor expounds on the difference between Asians and Americans, noting how even though Asian Americans look Asian, they are American at heart. Referencing a Hokkien term that means ‚Äúour kind of people,‚Äù she says that Asian Americans are not kaki lang. Remember, in this game, Eleanor is trying to create a winning hand comprising all matches of the same exact tile ‚Äî an ‚Äúextended family‚Äù that‚Äôs metaphorically composed of kaki lang.

The camera then cuts to show a number of discarded bamboo tiles. Discarded bamboo calls to mind a frequently used term for Westernized overseas Asians, this one Cantonese: jook sing, which literally means ‚Äúempty bamboo.‚Äù It‚Äôs a slang term that‚Äôs the Chinese equivalent of the Asian-American term ‚Äúbanana‚Äù ‚Äî yellow on the outside, white on the inside ‚Äî cited earlier in the film by Peik Lin (the frenetically hilarious Awkwafina). The ‚Äúempty‚Äù bamboo tiles are scattered alongside the tiles for East and West, not truly part of either, representing Eleanor‚Äôs perception of Rachel.

At this point, Rachel drops the bomb on Eleanor that Nick proposed to her, telling her that he said he‚Äôd be willing to walk away from everything ‚Äî his family, his family‚Äôs wealth ‚Äî to be with her. Right as Rachel is saying this, she draws the most important tile in the game: an eight of bamboo.

The number eight is of huge symbolic importance to the Chinese; it resembles the character for fortune and is considered a sign of wealth, prosperity, and happiness. It‚Äôs why so many Chinese license plates, phone numbers, and even street addresses contain eights. Monterey Park, the first city in San Gabriel Valley, California, to become a suburban destination for wealthy Chinese, was considered a particularly propitious place to live because it had an 818 area code.

While an eight doesn‚Äôt have special value in the game of mahjong, we see that the eight of bamboo is also the one tile Rachel needs to complete her hand. This is a winning tile for her. But Rachel knows something else, based on her observation of how the game has played out (remember, she‚Äôs a game theory professor!): It‚Äôs Eleanor‚Äôs winning tile too.

She then discloses to Eleanor that she turned Nick down. Eleanor is dumbfounded. ‚ÄúOnly a fool folds a winning hand,‚Äù she says, referring to Nick‚Äôs proposal.

This is critical, because in the very first scene of the movie, Rachel demonstrated through a poker game with one of her TAs that to be successful in any game where psychology and choice are a factor, you can‚Äôt play ‚Äúnot to lose‚Äù ‚Äî you have to play to win.

Rachel explains: When it comes to her marriage with Nick, Eleanor has guaranteed there‚Äôs no winning outcome for them. Nick choosing Rachel means he‚Äôd lose his mother and his family. Nick choosing his family means he might resent Eleanor forever ‚Äî thus losing his mother anyway. Lose-lose.

So she decided to seize control of the situation and choose for him. But she doesn‚Äôt want it to happen without Eleanor knowing exactly why it‚Äôs happening and what Rachel is giving up to make it possible.

She tells Eleanor that she knows Nick will eventually find someone else, someone that his family approves of ‚Äî that‚Äôs what every generation of Youngs has done before him, after all. And while her own heart will be broken, as she says, she loves him so much that she is willing to suffer if it means that Nick will keep the thing that is at the heart of Asian culture, and of his story: his family.

That‚Äôs when Rachel throws out the eight of bamboo as a discard ‚Äî folding her winning hand, knowing that Eleanor will pick it up and declare victory. While this happens, she explains that when Nick finds the proper match in the future, she wants Eleanor to understand that the only reason it occurred was because a ‚Äúpoor, raised by a single mother, low-class immigrant nobody‚Äù ‚Äî Rachel ‚Äî made it possible.

She then reveals her hand, which would have won, making it clear to the whole table what she‚Äôs done, and walks away.

In this move, Rachel has demonstrated to Eleanor three critical things. The first is that she loves Nick enough to put his future ahead of hers. The second is that she understands that family should always come first, something that Eleanor suspected she didn‚Äôt comprehend as a jook sing Asian American. And the third is that Rachel is strong, self-sacrificing, and courageous ‚Äî a lot like Eleanor herself. Instead of ‚Äúnever being enough‚Äù for Nick, a line Eleanor uses to surgically destroy Rachel in an earlier scene, she‚Äôs most likely exactly what Nick needs.

Knowing all of this context isn‚Äôt necessary for the scene to work, but it certainly adds depth to understand the symbolism of the game.

This essay was adapted from a post on Angry Asian Man. For a more detailed look at mahjong, read here.

Jeff Yang is a co-host of the podcast They Call Us Bruce, a featured contributor for CNN Opinion, and a columnist for South China Morning Post‚Äôs Inkstone magazine. His elder son, Hudson Yang, plays Eddie on ABC‚Äôs Fresh Off the Boat."

I just don't understand why the U.S. society likes to point out races. I just don't understand that. There are no different races, there is only one race, the human race, and it is composed by half-breeds (like me), Asians, Whites, Blacks, etc. Can't we just accept the fact that we are all humans and stop separating each other with that concept of 'race'? Title: CRAZY RICH ASIANS - Official Trailer
Comment: This movie might appear over-dramatized to fit the Hollywood appeal, but reading the books is honestly a whole other experience, especially from an Asian perspective. Kevin Kwan is incredibly perceptive and reveals many insider details on the lives of wealthy Asians because he himself grew up around similar types of people, studying in a private elite school in Singapore. Kwan understands the discrepancies between the various Asian cultures that exist and illustrates this through the treatment of Rachel Chu, who originates from mainland China, by rich Singaporean elites. On a side note, does Rachel and Nick remind anyone else of Prince Harry and Meghan Markle? Hauntingly similar things kept on appearing as I was reading and it's almost as if Kevin Kwan prophesied the royal wedding just a few years after the book release (e.g. Meghan Markle's real name is Rachel, both Meghan and Rachel are ostracized for being American, both couples met through a mutual friend etc.).

Title: CRAZY RICH ASIANS - Official Trailer
Comment:
Isn't it actually a good thing this could be a cliche movie?  Sure, it's great to have a predominately Asian cast for a revolutionary film, but wasn't the whole point that Asian people needed more representation in "regular" roles in media?  If you go too far into "let's make a super original film featuring Asian people" territory, you're probably going to get back to misrepresenting Asian stereotypes, so maybe it's a good thing to have a film that's more dealing with "regular problems."  I guess, if you call having a rich family abroad "regular problems."  

On other point, it does touch on the whole "Asian people feel White when abroad, but Asian in America; where do we call home?" and other identity issues which is also a much needed subject to be discussed today.

Comment: I am going to watch this movie, not because I think it looks like a good movie, but because it means something much more than that. This movie puts Asians in the lead roles in a film industry that rarely even includes Asians. The lead actors are all Asian and it is helping to bring Asians into the forefront of conversations. It's movies like this that will allow for the younger people to be more willing to step out from their comfort zones and go for unconventional careers; doctors, lawyers, computer engineers. I'm so excited for this movie for more than just the movie, but for what this movie represents to many of the Asian American communities and its youth.

Title: CRAZY RICH ASIANS - Official Trailer
Comment:
I know there‚Äôs a lot of people wondering why Asian-Americans are so excited for this movie when there‚Äôs a myriad variety of Korean/Chinese dramas and movies already existing. But the thing is, Asians and Asian-Americans are two vastly different populations with incredibly different cultures. Asians, people who live/grew up in Asia, have no problem finding representations of themselves in the media, whereas Asian-Americans see little to no representation of ourselves in American/Western media, our own countries. Asian-Americans have gravitated to Asian medias like anime, dramas, and kpop because, growing up, those were the only outlets we had seeing people who look like us being main characters in lead roles and music groups. It is part of our background, but it is still not quite us. The difference is that Asian-Americans grew up starved for true representation of themselves reflecting in the medias of their birth country. 

Instead, we grew up watching crude caricatures of ourselves, if we were ever reflected in Western media at all. They were roles written by people who didn‚Äôt and will never know what it‚Äôs like to be Asian or a POC. They were roles that lacked depth, creativity, and accuracy; simply existing to support a white lead character or to feign diversity. 

When it comes to whitewashing roles, Asians, like the Japanese, tend to be more okay with cultural appropriation, like white people playing Asian roles, because they are represented in their country‚Äôs media all the time, so appropriation doesn‚Äôt seem as much of a big deal to them. However, Asian-Americans don‚Äôt have this same luxury. What we get at best is a quirky side character every once in while who has to exhibit some form of tired stereotype. I can‚Äôt stress how incredibly unfair it is to be mocked for liking Asian stuff growing up (like anime etc.) and then as soon as it trends worldwide and is profitable, Western medias find a way to stick a white lead actor/actress into its remake somehow, when it would have been a clear opportunity for an Asian-American actor/actress to shine and represent the culture they came from. That is the reason why we want this, why we need more movies like this. I know that this movie has its flaws. Its representation does not reach the spectrum of diversity displayed in the book, but it‚Äôs a start. It‚Äôs a start we can build on and, therefore, a huge win for Asian representation in America and other Western countries!

Title: CRAZY RICH ASIANS - Official Trailer
Comment:
While I love the idea that Hollywood is representing Asians in a major way ( as compared to say art house flicks like Lion or Priyanka Chopra's supporting role in Baywatch or Hong Chau's turn in Downsizing or Angelababy in Independence Day 2),  the comments on this video, likening it to be like Black Panther for Black people or Love Simon for the lgbtq community is a bit of a fallacy. In those cases, these communities almost never get to see themselves represented in big budget blockbusters anywhere in the world. 

China meanwhile is almost about to overtake America as the largest film market in the world, they have plenty of home made blockbusters coming out every year that end up in the top 20-30 highest grossing movies worldwide. Japan has a thriving anime industry among other things. Hollywood has been emulating Korean action movies for years and India has the largest film industry in the world. So Asians see themselves represented on a regular basis on big screens and that is probably the reason why it took so long for Hollywood to make a movie exclusively about Asians because the appetites of the American asians were already being somewhat whetted.
